{"id":"2103.16166","submitter":"Nguyen Thanh Phuc","authors":"Nguyen Thanh Phuc","title":"Superreaction: the collective enhancement of a reaction rate by\n  molecular polaritons in the presence of energy fluctuations","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"The Journal of Chemical Physics 155, 014308 (2021)","doi":"10.1063/5.0052226","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph quant-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Recent experiments have demonstrated that molecular polaritons, hybrid states\nof light and matter formed by the strong coupling between molecular electronic\nor vibrational excitations and an optical cavity, can substantially modify the\nphysical and chemical properties of molecular systems. Here, we show that, by\nexploiting the collective character of molecular polaritons in conjunction with\nthe effect of polaron decoupling, i.e., the suppression of environmental\ninfluence on the polariton, a superreaction can be realized, involving a\ncollective enhancement of charge or excitation-energy transfer reaction rate in\na system of donors all coupled to a common acceptor. This effect is analogous\nto the phenomenon of superradiation. Since the polariton is a superposition\nstate of excitations of all the molecules coupled to the cavity, it is\nvulnerable to the effect of decoherence caused by energy fluctuations in\nmolecular systems. Consequently, in the absence of a strong light-matter\ninteraction, the reaction rate decreases significantly as the number of\nmolecules increases, even if the system starts from the polariton state. By\nturning on the light-matter interaction, the dynamic behavior of the system\nchanges dramatically, and the reaction rate increases with the number of\nmolecules, as expected for a superreaction. The underlying mechanism is shown\nto be the enhancement of quantum coherence between different donors as the\nlight-matter interaction becomes stronger.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 30 Mar 2021 08:46:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-08"}
